SPECIES COMMENTS: 2 immatures. Field notes on one individual seen close overhead with bins: "seen around  13:10 large head.  some mottling in the coverts. distinct white patch in the coverts towards the body on each side, armpits more or less.  some mottling, white, in the coverts, possibly some pale coloring in the tail. Flew over the ridge toward the north west, though direction not seen well due to trees."      While I ran to retrieve my camera, the two eagles and a few other raptors circled much higher on the draft. The two eagles I photographed may or may not be the same eagle I saw with bins.--   Photos: I believe I have included photos of the two individuals seen.  Some photos show marks of a second-year immature (i.e. white triangle on back behind head), and others show white mottling and axillary patches (more prominent when seen through bins than back-lit photographs shows, at least on one individual) more consistent with a juvenile.  Perhaps 1 juv. and one 2nd-year or either/both showing intermediary plumage.

LOCALITY: 700 Klamath Beach Road, Klamath, California, US (41.518, -124.041)
TRIP COMMENTS: We enjoyed our visit here yesterday so returned for another try for White-winged Crossbill. Habitats along this extraordinary loop include: nearshore ocean, rocky shores, quiet freshwater river and pond, Red Alder woodland, Sitka Spruce forest, brushy thickets, and Redwood forest.

Overlook first and then Coastal Drive, checking scattered clumps of Sitka Spruce and Red Alder groves. Very taken by the views of the of the picturesque sea stacks and wave-swept shore below. A brilliant interpretive sign revealed the reason for the dramatic scene here, the subduction zone lies right underneath one here. Finally, we scoped the lowermost Klamath River upstream to the US-101 bridge where we noted many Common Goldeneyes and Buffleheads, the lone Pacific Loon (seemed a little unusual to be upstream but possibly drawn to fresh water for whatever seemed to be bothering it.

TRIP COMMENTS: I spent all my time here on Old State Highway at the first pull out on the left overlooking the southeast corner of the lagoon. This is where the most recent sightings of the male Common Pochard, first found on Dec. 20, 2016. have been. There were large numbers of waterfowl on the lagoon but it didn't take long to spot the pochard.  Most of my larger numbers are certainly underestimated.  Since a majority of my time was spent scoping the lagoon the land birding suffered.  After a while two Oregon birders pulled up and just before I left a third Oregonian showed.  Other observers—Diane Pettey, Sally Hill; and Roger Robb.  09:35–11:25. Clear, not a cloud anywhere, calm, 2°/3°C

LOCALITY: Eel River Delta--Ferndale and Loleta Bottoms (General hotspot for historical entries)
TRIP COMMENTS: We intended to take US-299 west from Redding to the coast but slides had closed this main route. So, we detoured south to CA-36 and drove west from Red Bluff at a snails pace for hours through torrential rains. The creeks and rivers were all in flood and Califrnia Department of Transportation trucks were busy trying to keep this highway open, though slides were collapsing on the roadway as we crawled west and downward. We were very lucky to manage this crossing as just on reaching the coastal plain east of Fortuna, the highway was under water, and we followed a convoy-like procession of vehicles across the deluge. A bit later, highway officials closed this route, too!----The Ferndale Bottoms were extensively flooded, too, and even many roads under water. A real rain event this winter! Still, there were plenty of birds to see. A field full of Great Egrets was especially impressive, including a Cattle Egret, a waif from the south. We searched the several big gull flocks for the reported Glaucous, with no luck.

SPECIES COMMENTS: The immature bald eagle was attacking one of the Canada geese in the middle of the reservoir. It chased it down from behind  at about 20 feet above the water, knocked it to the surface and then continued to fly over and strike at it repeatedly.  After a few hits, the eagle landed on one of the trees sticking up out of the water.  The goose swam nearby for a few minutes then tried to fly away.  Again, the eagle knocked it out of the air into the water.  This time, on one of its strikes, it landed on the goose and seemed to be holding it under water.   After about a minute, the eagle took off and the goose popped right back up.  The eagle flew back to the tree, waited (or rested) and then tried a few more strikes.  The goose seemed to dive under water when it saw the eagle approaching.  Finally, the eagle gave up and left the area.

Kern River Valley Bald Eagle info: 11 June 2017, Tillie Creek Campground, mid morning observe two adult Bald Eagles flying together.  They flew to the mouth of the Kern River, thence up river.  They were a male and a female by virtue of very noticeable size difference.  I speculated that they either did not nest this year or that their nesting attempt failed, based on the fact that the adult female typically stays close to the nest as long as there are young on the nest.  So if there was an active nest in the valley with young, the adult female would likely be close by.  In fact, I observed an active Bald Eagle nest in San Luis Obispo Co. on 15 June '17 with two ready to fledge chicks and the adult female was perched beside the nest.  However, there are always exceptions.   Further, one of Alison's interns-Nicholas Gabry-reported seeing a young Bald Eagle adjacent to Camp 9 on 30 June '17.  His description indicated that he did see a young Bald Eagle, but he didn't see, or remember, enough detail to determine if the bird was a fresh juv, or an immature.  More intrigue!

TRIP COMMENTS: Sighting lasted approx 30 seconds while descending the ramp onto eastbound Hy 37 from northbound 101.  There was no traffic, and I slowed from 45mph to 20mph.  Sighting was through the windshield without binocs.  The view was uninterrupted and the elevation was advantageous.  While in sight, the bird was flying southeast from near Deer Island across Hy 37 to above Bel Marin Keys.  Flight was straight, steady, and level at no higher than 100' above terrain.
SPECIES COMMENTS: Unmistakable adult Bald Eagle.  View was from the side, more dorsal than ventral.  Body and wings all appeared uniformly dark, while entire head and neck, and entire tail, were white.  Head and neck projected enough to nearly visually balance the tail.  Wingbeat was steady, unbroken, measured, full with fully flexing broad wings, especially on the upbeat, which matched the downbeat in strength and size of arc.  Body remained steady during flap.
Adult

LOCALITY: Tule Lake NWR--League of Nations (MOD Co.)
TRIP COMMENTS: Birding with Gerry Hill. Noticeably absent: any white geese!

Blustery and cool so landbirds were keeping hidden. Drove Auto Tour Route. We particularly were moved by the sight of a cloud of white geese, no doubt mostly Snows, that wheeled and called in the sky, truly a fantastic spectacle!

We were lucky to be in a pronounced rainshadow of the major "atmospheric river," a series of Pacific storms slamming northern California. Here we enjoyed gray overcast skies and only a light breeze. The lake was mostly frozen, with only the edges with open water. We noted two sparrow-sized birds flush from the roadside near the end of the pavement and saw they flew east to the lake edge. So, we set out to see what they were. Though I was thinking they might be Lapland Longspurs, they turned out to be Horned Larks. Darn!----Raptors were a treat with two Golden Eagles and five Rough-legged Hawks, our highest count of any site on this trip.

Drove County Rd. 115 north-to south, then US-395 north to outskirts of Alturas. Habitats covered: ponds, agricultural fields both flooded and dry (lots of standing water everywhere!), shrub-steppe, grasslands with greasewood cover. Our best bird was American Tree Sparrow, a new species for us in California.
Surprise Valley was windy and cool, but we were impressed with the raptor show, especially Golden Eagles, a bird we always love to watch!
Watched the PRFAs put on a great show that included them calling frequently, copulating, and visiting probable nest sites.

LOCALITY: Tule Lake NWR--Auto Tour and Sump 1B (MOD Co.)
TRIP COMMENTS: Still needing Barrow's Goldeneyes, we covered the auto tour route finding most open water frozen.The several small areas of open water were choked with waterfowl, creating quite a spectacle. We wondered if the grebes remaining in the small (some just two metres in diameter) open leads were trapped, and thus there's the question whether birds lingering too long here will likely succumb. One interesting observation we had was of a Golden Eagle perched next to a Red-tailed Hawk, a sight I don't believe we've witnessed before in all our years of birding.

SPECIES COMMENTS: of special interest was not only that there were two Bald Eagles seen, which is interesting given that one adult out of a nesting pair earlier this spring was electrocuted, and  that there  now appears to be an associated pair again (but I don't know if either one or both is related to the Bald Eagles seen in spring). Two adult Bald Eagles were acting in tandem to fatigue an American Coot, by circling over a lone coot on the eastern edge of the lake, with each pass of one of the eagles would harrass the coot which  would dive and the eagle would fly on. On one pass, one of the eagles actually dove, with talons down, dropping into the water to catch the coot, but emerged "empty taloned". Many passes later by both eagles, it appeared that the coot would make it to shore and near the cover of some boat mooring structures which would make it difficult for the eagles to take the coot. The coot was successfully diving at each pass of an eagle. The eagles were circling and were about 180 degrees apart, so an eagle harrassed the coot for each half of a circle. At the last time the coot was above water, its entire body was  mostly above water line. In previous passes it only had its head above water before diving. It appeared to be a Pied-billed Grebe at times. But on the last dive it made, an eagle sent its talons into the water and the eagle became submerged to its upper breast. It stayed there motionless, and at first I thought that it had missed it. After a few moments I knew that it had struck the coot underwater, and was now holding it underwater to drown it. After about a minute the eagle began moving its wings in a sweeping motion towards the shore, "swimming" with each stroke, and making it shore where it hauled some larger object in its talons ashore, and it shook its feathers, but still stood atop the large dark object. Then in the edge of the binocular field of view I saw the other adult eagle swoop upon a coot on shore, just some 35-40 yards away from the other eagle, and that eagle also caught a coot. The second caught coot was immediately hauled away across the lake, towards Park 3 I suppose, and not long after that, the "swimming" Bald Eagle took off with its prey in the same direction. I could see the green lobed dangling feet of the coots and dark bodies of the coots that each eagle had caught. It's interesting that coots seem to be a common food item for Bald Eagles as I see them feed on American Coots during winter in the Klamath Basin.

TRIP COMMENTS: Observers: Patricia Clark, Steve and Diane Rose. 35 degrees and snow on the ground. The reservoir is very low.

At 6 a.m. I met at the Starbucks near Lake of the Pines with all members of my Area 7, Lake of the Pines section of the Auburn Christmas Bird Count.  I split us up into four teams and we all headed off to our designated areas until meeting up at noon for lunch and to see what species we had found and where we might go to find potential species missed earlier.  As she has for Lyann Comrack birded with me all day as she has for about 15 CBCs.  The totals below represent what we found in our portion of Area 7.  It was 44F when we started counting at the sewage ponds at 7:10 a.m. During this sunny day with some breeze, we drove 34.7 miles and walked 2.53 miles (distance measured by my Fitbit). Unfortunately, nobody puts out birdseed now so the nice flocks near the buildings were not present.  The number of species was good here at the ponds but the number of individuals was low, except for 3 Virginia Rails and 3 Soras. Last year no rails responded to my playback. I always enjoy seeing all the Hooded Mergansers here and usually at a tiny pond near Lake Combie.  The pair of adult Bald Eagles seen at the nest by Tom Horner and Jim Thomas around 7:15 a.m. were absent when we looked around 2:30 p.m. but we did see a first year Bald Eagle twice. ----Lake of the Pines itself was a great disappointment. From 1980 on when the new person on my team had to try to count the  American Coots whose numbers were as high as 1,725 in 1993, the waters have had some type of treatment that drastically reduced most species and even eliminated some.  This year we found on small flock of 14 American Coots. It is sad! ----Due to fear of fires, the area Lyann and I cover has had most, if not all, understory plants removed in the pine/oak forest around the homes to reduce fire fuel.  This has also reduced the number of individuals of many species. In spite of it all, we still enjoy this count every year.

TRIP COMMENTS: Local report of an adult Bald Eagle in a large eucalyptus tree along Crown Valley Blvd. in Dana Point at the junction with Laguna Niguel. Note: wing tag information identifies this bird as "Shasta", an almost 4 year old female bird fledged from Catalina Is. in June 2013. Bird was previously sighted in Washington State in 2014 and Oregon in 2015.

TRIP COMMENTS: Jim Thomas arrived at 7:30 a.m. today to help me scout Area 8 of the Folsom CBC, which I will join on Sunday.  WE first attempted to drive into Beal's Point Campground but there was nobody at the entrance kiosk and I did not know if either of my passes would work.  We then drove to the entrance of Folsom Lake Park where I learned both my passes were no good and we paid the $12 daily entrance fee.  Here is where we started our eBird count.  I did not know this area at all so this was a hit and miss day of checking out as many different roads and trails as possible before we called it quits about 2:30 p.m.----We estimated short walks from the vehicle at about .5 miles and I used MapMyWalk to learn we walked 1.6 miles after we arrived at the furthest parking lot in this park.  As often as possible we scoped the lake. The best bird was the 2nd year Bald Eagle that Jim spotted at the first huge parking lot.  He also spotted a Rock Wren before I even got out of the car.  We could see lots of Western/Clark's grebes far out on the lake but I only felt confident about 1 Clark's and about a dozen Westerns.  All the rest were simply too far out.----There were very few gulls, but we did pick out 1 Ring-billed and 1 Herring gulls and two small flocks of California Gulls.  We really had to work hard for the California Thrasher (see in chaparral) on our 1.6 mile hike on trails mostly used by mountain bikers.  Some of the jumps they put in were so scary we wondered how many broken bones they caused.  I was sure we would get response from a Blue-gray Gnatcatcher on chaparral portion of that trail, but none responded.  I was bummed that we never heard or saw a California Quail or a Wild Turkey.  I had expected both of them.  ----It was really fun to explore a new location and often guess correctly at what birds I could get to respond in certain habitats that looked perfect for them.  ----Now that I have been there, I need to talk with Scott Hoppe who is the leader in Area 8 and figure out which of those places he wants me to cover on Sunday.  We were happy with our 65 species plus two taxa, but wonder how many more had we started at 7 a.m. when Folsom Lake Park opens and stayed till late afternoon.

TRIP COMMENTS: Howard King and I, joined for much of the time by Tony Metcalf and briefly by Chet McGaugh, spent the morning checking the Walker Ponds and adjacent hunting clubs.  Howard and I began our visit along the road near the Walker Parking Lot, where we spent an extended period of time studying and taking photos of the continuing American Golden-Plover that had been found by Tony the previous afternoon.  After our time spent with this bird, we walked a counterclockwise loop around Pond W4 returning to the vicinity of the parking lot, where we met up with Tony.  Together, we drove south to the far end of the Walker Ponds and roughly a kilometer beyond to check not only the ponds on the wildlife area but also adjacent ponds on both the Ramona Hunt Club and the Mystic Lake Duck Club.  Upon returning to the wildlife area, we drove a counterclockwise loop that took us around the perimeter of Ponds W4-10 before returning and joining Chet near the parking lot where we began.  We concentrated on the Walker Ponds along this loop and only glanced at the many (but also generally distant) birds on Mystic Lake, which are not included in this list.  On our return to the parking lot, we again studied the plover before Howard and I left the site without checking the main part of the wildlife area north of the San Jacinto River corridor.  Given the rains over the winter, the ponds were generally quite full, yet some had mudflats of varying extent.  The plover was seen on a shallow pond on the hunting club that had little water and extensive flats, but most ponds provided only limited habitat for small shorebirds.  We did our best to count the shorebirds and ducks, but the extent of area covered made it difficult to arrive at precise numbers for many of the species encountered.  Many totals in this list are therefore probably best considered relatively accurate estimates as opposed to direct counts, and our coverage of the site for land birds was quite superficial.  It was clear and essentially calm for most of the morning, but likely with a mild breeze late in our visit that I essentially failed to notice, and with temperatures increasing from the mid-50s to the mid-70s during our extended visit.  7:35 am - 12:40 pm.

What a day this has been!  Jim Thomas and Marc Tessier arrived at 7:30 a.m. on a day that had been predicted to rain, but we had none.  I spread seed out when they arrived and we gave birds 10-15 minutes to arrive, but shortly the yard was empty, meaning accipiter nearby.  We went out the gate and had a juvenile and adult in 5-10 minutes.  It was about 39F when we headed  over to the Pond overlook.  It was most comfortable when we found a sunny spot to stand in as we scanned the still high river flowing out of the former pond.  Best was Jim spotting the adult Bald Eagle as it flew into a tall cottonwood, but this time instead of perching on top, it landed behind part of the main trunk.  Not the best viewing conditions, but still great to have.  Each of us has days when we seem to be on fire spotting the rarer species and today it was Jim's turn, over and over again.----We birded our way down to the Rock Diagonal and then to the Gristmill Gravel Bar overlook.  Jim picked out the male Phainopepla today while I got lucky spotting the female.  Marc picked out one of the two White-tailed Kites.  As we crossed over the Gristmill Access parking lot, I asked if Marc would like to try looking into my Wood Duck boxes in hopes of seeing a lifer Western Screech-Owl.  He said. "Yes" so we returned to my home to get pine shavings, the ladder, and other tools.  This turned out to be great for me since I got to check all the Wood Duck boxes and replace the wet pine wood shavings in most of them.  We removed two complete Fox Squirrel nests, but found no owl.  Best was one of my boxes that had 5 Wood Duck eggs.----While Marc and I worked on the Wood Duck nest boxes, Jim spent time scoping for birds from several of our overlooks.  Best was finding the male American Kestrel.  The Sandhill Cranes were moving north today.  We had four groups:  42 (Jim), 38 (Marc), I think 15 and 7.  Jim will correct me when he gets this report.  We all ate some slices of the huge pizza Laurie brought back from Costco yesterday and both Jim and Marc left with a bag of tangerines...more left for others who come birding soon.----As I was starting to write these comments, there were as many as 11 Anna's Hummingbirds on the large nectar feeder three feet away from me.  There may have been more individuals around as I watched some arrive and some leave.  At one point 8 were perched and three were waiting for a space to land...wonderful way to end the day!

TRIP COMMENTS: It started as a cold, but non-foggy, sunny morning with little to no breeze for the Cosumnes River Preserve Field Trip #1 led by Jeri Langham and Ted Beedy.  We left the hotel at 6:30 a.m. and convened in the upper parking lot at Cosumnes River Preserve. Participants were: Angela Boyle , Nancy Bruce, Gayle Hackamack, Cheryl Horsley, Paula Kayton, Joan Kent, Kate Kramer, Tony McKinney, Joan Parker, Eric Ross, and Doreen Yates.  After a brief orientation, we headed across the street to scope the large ponds in the  CRP Lost Slough area getting our first great looks at the Sandhill Cranes and more rare Ring-necked Ducks. We drove to the second parking lot and walked out the boardwalk finding our target Blue-winged Teal. We then drove further north on Franklin Blvd. and scanned from the RR crossover on Desmond Road.  As we worked the ponds along Desmond, I noticed that the dirt road to the "Barn" was already open and since we had permission enter, we did. Amazing were the number of Tree Swallows flying all around the nest boxes and elsewhere along this stretch. Two hundred is probably an underestimate. Even better was again seeing the single adult Barn Swallow from the parking area of the "Barn" that was not even on the eBird list for this time of year. Turning left as we returned to Desmond Road, I stopped to try to look for the Ross's/Snow Goose we had seen land. But then I glimpsed an adult Bald Eagle. From the "Barn" we had watched a female Northern Harrier eating a prey item on a distant levee.  Three Turkey Vultures chased it off and they were replaced by a Red-tailed Hawk. As we watched the Bald Eagle, it replaced the Red-tailed Hawk...talk about watching unusual nature interactions!!!  The white goose then landed close enough for us to confirm it as a Ross's Goose.----Our next goal was to bird the trail to "The Point".  We were a very fortunate group in having lots of luck drawing birds in with my playback and seeing many because of skilled participants.  This skill was best shown when we found the flock of 40-60 birds at "The Point" and with all eyes searching and my laser to help with directions, we found all our main targets.  I believe some might have named our return trip to our cars, "Langham's death march."  But we did get back to Stockton in time for lunch and the meeting!----My thanks to all of you for making this such a wonderful adventure!
SPECIES COMMENTS: Adult

SPECIES COMMENTS: Adult seen standing on what appeared to be complete nest structure - very substantial construction. Bird was not crouched down as would be expected with an egg, but standing upright. After we looked away for a few minutes and then looked back, the bird was no longer on the platform, but one adult, presumably the same, perched about 40 feet away in a nearby tree. Not likely incubating, but apparently investigating the structure for possible nesting attempt this year.

TRIP COMMENTS: 61 F, 100% sunny. Birding with Sophie Webb and her dog. At the end of the public road which is actually signposted as Santa Anita Road, but shows as McCreery Ranch Road on Google maps.
SPECIES COMMENTS: An interesting record. I have seen fledged bald eagles along this end of the road, and have wondered if there could be another breeding pair in this general area, especially on the private ranch at the end of this road.

LOCALITY: Quien Sabe Rd.--Santa Anita Rd. to end of public road
TRIP COMMENTS: 55 F, 50% cloud cover., breezy from the north. Some flowers are beginning to show. California buckeye is leafing out. The total length of this road is 4.6 miles.
SPECIES COMMENTS: This is the presumed, Bernadette of the pair with Bob as her mate. She is incubating in the same nest as last year (which is the same nest site when I first discovered it in 2004). Although the branches supporting the nest crashed (between October 2014 and January 2015), this pair rebuilt the nest that same season and fledged one young. Except for that year, (2014) and one other year when the male was shot dead, they have fledged two young every year. They primarily feed on ground squirrels which I confirmed by sitting and watching them catch the squirrels. This nest is on PRIVATE LAND. DO NOT TRESPASS. The property owner is aware of the nest. .

SPECIES COMMENTS: PRIVATE PROPERTY. NO PUBLIC ACCESS. CLOSELY MONITORED NEST. It is a violation of the Bald & Golden Eagle Act to harass or disturb these birds in any way. Today it appeared that Bob, the male was incubating the egg(s) while Bernadette was consuming some prey while she sat atop a nearby oak. According to birdsna.org, females incubate 72% of the time, males incubate the remainder of the time. Only occasionally do they leave the nest unattended. They may cover the eggs if so.

TRIP COMMENTS: 59 F, 98% cloud cover. There is a lot of water in the reservoir for the first time in years. It still has a ways to go to reach levels that I have seen in the past, especially 1998 El Nino winter. But, this is a good start. Two guys who bought a piece of property south of here (007 Ranch), stopped to talk with me. I drove south of the entrance to Clear Creek BLM area, but did not enter because the amount of water flowing in the creek was very high. On my return drive I saw about 45 tule elk on the far side of the reservoir. It is truly wonderful to see this much water flowing in south county. I was surprised to not find more ducks, though. Perhaps, the bald eagles are having an impact on that.
SPECIES COMMENTS: Bald eagles have been known to nest at this location in the past. However, the nest was never visible, being on private property and well away from viewing along the road. That nest was in a large gray pine. I was surprised and thrilled to find this new nest today. It is also on PRIVATE PROPERTY. DO NOT TRESPASS. Bald eagles are protected from harassment or disturbance by the Bald & Golden Eagle Act. This nest is monitored.

57 F warming to 82 F by the time I left. Ultimately, temperatures would reach 110 F today and are forecast to continue for the next two days. 100% clear; no wind at all. I walked around a good bit, but never left the reservoir proper area. The water level continues to recede and only the far north end has any water. It appears to be very shallow. Water level is controlled by the county. There is a good stand of shoulder-high "weeds" surrounding the single willow tree. These weeks are proving excellent for migrants. Ultimately, the weeds will probably be mowed down by the county. The reservoir sits on Paicines Ranch property, private property. They have no control over the water level or mowing of the weeds. It is possible for birders to rent cottages at this ranch, which I highly recommend. Once again, I should have arrived earlier in the morning.
SPECIES COMMENTS: Per my last report: she flew in about 8:15 a.m., from the southwest, straight over the reservoir, putting most of the ducks up in the air, circled to the east once she reached the north end, and headed straight for the small oak along the levee.

SPECIES COMMENTS: Truly amazing that this adult female bald eagle was sitting at her winter site near the valley where she nests. The site fidelity to the area is incredible. One of this pair is on site for some 10 months of the year. This would be Bernadette of the pair, Bob & Bernadette. It appears that the nest has already been refurbished. I wonder if they need to maintain site fidelity to prevent the golden eagles from taking over their nest site. This happened once, years ago when two golden eagles sat right at the nest. The bald eagles had taken it back by 10 a.m. the next morning. Certainly, they do compete with the golden eagles for the ground squirrel prey.

TRIP COMMENTS: 70 F; 98% cloud cover; no wind; about 40 raindrops fell. By 9:30 a.m. it was 83 F; 100% cloud cover; < 3mph wind. A recent severe heat wave hit the county for the past three days. Temperatures were recorded above 120 F.  The cloud cover and raindrops of today are the influence of a hurricane off Baja moving northward. The water level in the reservoir continues to recede. I forgot my spotting scope (having just done 3 back to back long pelagic trips.) I walked (with permission) to the willow tree and a little beyond. Please do not trespass and remain in the pullout. Water level is controlled by the county, although this reservoir sits on private property, Paicines Ranch.

LOCALITY: Quien Sabe Rd.--Santa Anita Rd. to end of public road
TRIP COMMENTS: 60 F, hazy, but sunny; 1% cloud cover; < 5mph. Saw one black-tailed deer. Since I moved to Hollister in 1996, this road has continued to remain one of the best examples of open grasslands/blue oak savannah. It is primarily cattle grazing on ranches that takes place along the public road. There are no disked fields along any portion of this road. Beautiful countryside.
SPECIES COMMENTS: This is presumably, the pair, "Bob & Bernadette," who have nested at this location since 2004. The female was standing in the nest while the male was perched about 10 feet from the nest on an oak tree branch. This pair usually has the nest rebuilt by at least Thanksgiving. In recent years, they have refurbished the nest as early as late October. Sal Lucido refers to this pair as an "advanced" pair. Since I began watching this nest in 2004, twentyfive eaglets have fledged from the nest. One of the Golden Eagles was perched atop an oak in the same valley.

SPECIES COMMENTS: Leucistic subadult, probably third-year bird. This was the first observation of this individual, but it was subsequently seen widely on the central coast - in San Benito and San Mateo Counties, and then in the North Bay. The bird was not banded. Dark tips to the rectrices, with an all-white head. Almost all of the feathers on the bird that should be dark brown (primaries, secondaries, tertials, under- and upperwing coverts, body feathers, and leg feathers) were beige or mottled white and pale brown. It was eating a fish on the berm between the two large ponds north of the model airplane park entrance road when I first saw it, but it then flew to a sycamore next to the first large pond on the south side of the entrance road, and it later caught a large fish in that pond and ate it.
Interesting leucistic individual!

After 5 minutes, the adult started calling and a few minutes later flew over closer to the youngster. After another 2 minutes the youngster flew off to a Ponderosa pine. The adult flew in almost immediately. The youngster had been perfectly balanced on the small branch, but one of the adult's legs kept slipping down. Stayed there for some minutes, then moved to top of Ponderosa pine across from young eagle and above red-tail.

TRIP COMMENTS: Meiss Lake in the Butte Valley Wildlife Area was our first birding stop in California. Here we drove the levee road encircling part of the lake. Raptors we enjoyed observing included both Ferruginous Hawk and Golden Eagle. We also noted lots of waterfowl, a signal the fall migration was underway. Shorebirds were still obvious, too. We were impressed to see over 550 Long-billed Dowitchers in four or so loose groups, seven Pectoral Sandpipers, and a sizable flock of Least Sandpipers. On the late side were a few Black-necked Stilts.

Central Valley Bird Club Field Trip with Middle Mountain Interpretive Hikes. Mid-50s to near 80 F. Fairly calm for most of the day despite a forecast of considerable wind. Total walking distance about 6 miles (eBird distance reduced to account for back-tracking). Several tree frogs, many fence lizards, a deer mouse sp. near the parked vehicles, many pipevine swallowtails and a few each anise swallowtails and Sara orangetips. And can't forget the many golden-haired dung flies adorning the cow fresh cow pies near the parking area. We walked past the two ponds and near "Anvil Rock." This list only includes birds from last vehicle creek crossing, around the parking area, and the hike.

TRIP COMMENTS: With Linda Frazier and Marilyn Harding.  Scouting Lake Casitas County Park for a field trip for my bird class.  We first drove over to the "reservoir" area of the lake, which had the most dabbling ducks, then went and parked where the road was barricaded and walked south towards the eagle nest at "Tea Cup" camp site and return.  Weather:  cloudy, some rain showers, temps. in high 50 deg. F.
SPECIES COMMENTS: As we watched nearby, the adult male Bald Eagle approached the nest tree area.  He was carrying a fish.  He perched in the dead Eucalyptus tree near the nest tree, and proceeded to eat the fish, which he devoured quickly.  He then spent a lot of time cleaning and sharpening his bill by rubbing it continuously from side to side along the smooth Eucalyptus branch on which he was perched.  He then flew away, and we watched him as he soared out over the lake and around the "island".  No other eagles were present.

This adult has been seen for some time here.--  When this adult was on the northwest shoreline an immature "dark belly" eagle landed next to the adult as if begging for food. The adult had no food and ignored the immature begging. The adult was not hostile to the young bird.--   There may have been more than one immature bird. We saw one soaring high and disappear into a northeast canyon then very shortly afterward we saw an immature bird with the adult on the shoreline.

TRIP COMMENTS: Following up on earlier reports of a Townsend's Solitaire in the area. Keith Bailey and Jason Riggio showed up shortly after I arrived and we birded together for much of the time, including a brief foray up the road to the campground. The rains started around 9:00 and they headed home around 9:30 after we stopped briefly at the campground. I decided to make another stop at the main parking lot where I eventually had the solitaire just as I had decided to head home for the day.
SPECIES COMMENTS: Three immatures soaring together with a Golden Eagle also soaring nearby for comparison. Keith and Jason saw an adult just before I met up with them.

SPECIES COMMENTS: Immature bird, probably first year, soaring high and to the west of Catalina. It soared off farther west. Massive size with very long head/beak, light-colored beak/lores, rectangular wing profile with separated primaries (like Turkey Vulture), flat soaring wings (not like Turkey Vulture), mottled white on black under wings and body - thin white lines extending into the wings from the axillaries and whitish tail with dark terminal band.
Flying overhead among what looked like a small group of Greater White-fronted Geese, very strange.
